import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import DetailHeader from "../../components/DetailHeader.astro";
import DetailPostLayout from "../../layouts/DetailPostLayout.astro";

import oldMenuImage from '../../assets/projects/natsu/natsu-old-menu.jpg';
import verticalMenuImage from '../../assets/projects/natsu/natsu-vertical.png';
import horizontalMenuImage from '../../assets/projects/natsu/natsu-horizontal.png';
---

<DetailPostLayout
  title="Natsu Menu Redesign"
  description="A UX case study on transforming a restaurant's ordering tool, improving usability, and elevating the brand experience through user-centric design."
  keywords="UX design, UI design, information architecture, food photography, restaurant menu design, user experience, case study"
>
  <div class="post">
    <main class="post-wrapper">
      <DetailHeader
        tag="UX/UI DESIGN & PHOTOGRAPHY"
        description="Feb - Mar 2022">
        <h1 class="font-type">
          Natsu Menu Redesign
        </h1>
      </DetailHeader>

      <section class="natsu-content">

        <div class="overview-section">
          <div class="section-heading"><span class="section-number">01</span><h2>Project Overview</h2></div>
          <div class="section-content"><p>Natsu is a popular Japanese restaurant in Tampere's central market hall. While working there as a cashier, I gained firsthand insight into a critical operational bottleneck: the menu. It was not only hindering the customer's ordering experience but also failing to reflect the restaurant's quality. Recognizing the opportunity to apply my design skills to a real-world problem, I initiated a complete redesign to solve these tangible issues.</p></div>
        </div>
        <div class="before-after-section">
            <div class="section-heading"><span class="section-number">02</span><h2>The Problem: A Usability Bottleneck</h2></div>
            <div class="grid-2-col">
                <div class="text-content">
                    <h3 class="subsection-heading">Identified Pain Points</h3>
                    <p>The original menu suffered from critical usability and design flaws that directly impacted both customer experience and business operations.</p>
                    <ul class="pain-points-list">
                        <li><strong>Poor Usability & Accessibility:</strong> Low-contrast text was difficult to read in dim lighting. Food images were disconnected from their descriptions, forcing users to hunt for information and increasing their <strong>cognitive load</strong>.</li>
                        <li><strong>Lack of Information Architecture:</strong> Dishes were listed without logical grouping. New items were appended randomly, creating a confusing and overwhelming list that hindered efficient decision-making.</li>
                        <li><strong>Inconsistent Brand Image:</strong> An amateur, presentation-software aesthetic was inconsistent with the restaurant's established reputation, diminishing the overall brand experience.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="image-content">
                    <Image src={oldMenuImage} alt="A photo of the old, cluttered Natsu menu" class="full-width-image" style="border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--color-border);" />
                    <p style="text-align: center; font-style: italic; opacity: 0.8; margin-top: 1rem;">The original menu lacked structure and readability.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="design-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">03</span>
            <h2>The Solution: Interactive Design Showcase</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="section-content">

            <h3 class="subsection-heading">1. Rebuilding the Information Architecture</h3>
            <p>My first priority was to create order from chaos. By applying core IA principles, I grouped all dishes into logical categories (Donburi, Stir-fried, Katsu, etc.). This structure aligns with customers' <strong>mental models</strong>, allowing them to navigate the options intuitively and significantly <strong>reducing cognitive load</strong>.</p>
            
            <h3 class="subsection-heading">2. Enhancing Visual Design & Usability</h3>
            <p>To address readability, I switched to a high-contrast theme with a light background and clean typography, establishing a clear <strong>visual hierarchy</strong>. I applied the <strong>Gestalt principle of Proximity</strong> by placing each dish's photo directly adjacent to its name and description, making the connection effortless. Additionally, I introduced clear <strong>visual cues</strong>, like a 'V' icon for vegetarian options, to streamline the selection process for all users.</p>

            <h3 class="subsection-heading">3. Strengthening the Brand & Photography</h3>
            <p>A key part of elevating the brand was replacing the old imagery. <strong>I personally directed, shot, and post-processed all the food photography.</strong> High-quality visuals not only stimulate appetite but also convey the quality of the food and build brand trust. Finally, to accommodate different use cases, I developed two distinct layouts:</p>

            <div class="carousel">
              <div class="carousel-slides">
                <div class="carousel-slide active" data-slide="0">
                  <h4>Vertical Layout</h4>
                  <p class="caption">Optimized for exterior displays and single-user viewing, this layout follows a natural top-to-bottom reading flow.</p>
                  <Image src={verticalMenuImage} alt="Vertical layout of the new menu" />
                </div>
                <div class="carousel-slide" data-slide="1">
                  <h4>Horizontal Layout</h4>
                  <p class="caption">Ideal for in-store tabletop use, the grid allows multiple people to easily scan and compare different sections.</p>
                  <Image src={horizontalMenuImage} alt="Horizontal layout of the new menu" />
                </div>
              </div>
              <button class="carousel-button prev">
                <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg>
              </button>
              <button class="carousel-button next">
                <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg>
              </button>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insight-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">04</span>
            <h2>Outcome & Impact</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="insight-content">
            <p>The redesigned menu delivered measurable positive results, validating the power of applying a UX mindset to a physical product. The restaurant adopted both designs for different contexts.</p>
            <div class="goals-cards" style="grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));">
              <div class="goals-card">
                <h4>Increased Engagement</h4>
                <p>"The new poster menu noticeably increased the number of passersby who stopped to look, directly increasing foot traffic."</p>
              </div>
              <div class="goals-card">
                <h4>Streamlined Ordering</h4>
                <p>"Staff and customers reported that the clear photos and categories dramatically reduced ordering time and questions, improving service efficiency."</p>
              </div>
              <div class="goals-card">
                <h4>Improved Brand Perception</h4>
                <p>"Regular customers expressed high satisfaction, noting the new menu felt more professional and aligned with the quality of the food they loved."</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="research-section">
            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="section-number">05</span>
                <h2>Personal Reflection</h2>
            </div>
            <div class="section-content">
                <div class="user-groups-highlight">
                    <p>This project proved to me that the core principles of UX—understanding users, organizing information, and optimizing for usability—are universal. They apply just as effectively to a physical menu as they do to a digital app.</p>
                </div>
                <p>This project wasn't assigned; it was born from observing a real-world problem and taking the initiative to solve it. Managing the entire lifecycle, from analysis and strategy to hands-on photography and implementation, was an invaluable experience that solidified my understanding of the holistic design process and the joy of creating tangible value.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
  </div>
</DetailPostLayout>

<script>
  // --- CAROUSEL JAVASCRIPT ---
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const carousel = document.querySelector('.carousel');
    if (!carousel) return;

    const slides = carousel.querySelectorAll('.carousel-slide');
    const prevButton = carousel.querySelector('.carousel-button.prev');
    const nextButton = carousel.querySelector('.carousel-button.next');
    let currentIndex = 0;

    function showSlide(index) {
      // Loop back to the start if we go past the end
      if (index >= slides.length) {
        currentIndex = 0;
      }
      // Loop to the end if we go before the beginning
      else if (index < 0) {
        currentIndex = slides.length - 1;
      }
      else {
        currentIndex = index;
      }
      
      // Hide all slides
      slides.forEach(slide => {
        slide.classList.remove('active');
      });

      // Show the correct one
      slides[currentIndex].classList.add('active');
    }

    // Event listeners for the buttons
    nextButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
      showSlide(currentIndex + 1);
    });

    prevButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
      showSlide(currentIndex - 1);
    });

    // Show the first slide initially
    showSlide(currentIndex);
  });
</script>

<style>
  /* --- NEW CAROUSEL STYLES --- */
  .carousel {
    position: relative;
    max-width: 900px; /* Adjust max-width as needed */
    margin: 3rem auto 0; /* Centered with top margin */
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary, rgba(255,255,255,0.03));
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border, rgba(255,255,255,0.1));
    border-radius: 12px;
    padding: 2rem;
  }
  .carousel-slides {
    /* This container ensures consistent height */
    min-height: 550px; /* Adjust if needed */
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
  }
  .carousel-slide {
    display: none; /* All slides are hidden by default */
    text-align: center;
    width: 100%;
  }
  .carousel-slide.active {
    display: block; /* Only the active slide is shown */
  }
  .carousel-slide h4 {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .carousel-slide .caption {
    margin-top: 0;
    max-width: 60ch;
    opacity: 0.9;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    margin-left: auto;
    margin-right: auto;
  }
  /* This is the key to controlling the image size! */
  .carousel-slide img {
    max-height: 500px; /* The tall vertical menu will shrink to this height */
    width: auto;
    max-width: 100%;
    display: block;
    margin: 0 auto;
    border-radius: 8px;
  }
  .carousel-button {
    position: absolute;
    top: 50%;
    transform: translateY(-50%);
    background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border, rgba(255,255,255,0.1));
    color: white;
    border-radius: 50%;
    width: 40px;
    height: 40px;
    cursor: pointer;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    transition: background-color 0.2s ease;
  }
  .carousel-button:hover {
    background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.6);
  }
  .carousel-button.prev {
    left: -20px;
  }
  .carousel-button.next {
    right: -20px;
  }
  @media (max-width: 950px) {
    .carousel-button.prev { left: 10px; }
    .carousel-button.next { right: 10px; }
  }


  /* All your other styles remain below */
  .hero-container { margin-bottom: 4rem; }
  /* ... (rest of your existing CSS) ... */
